 range of case studies, from motets, trouvère song, plays, romance, vernacular translations, and proverb collections, to show that medieval composers "ed refrains as vernacular auctoritates; she argues that their appropriation of scholastic, Latinate writing techniques workedto authorize Old French music and poetry as media suitable for the transmission of knowledge. Beginning with an exploration of the quasi-scholastic usage of refrains in anonymous and less familiar clerical contexts, the book goeson to articulate a new framework for understanding the emergence of the first two named authors of vernacular polyphonic music, the cleric-trouvères Adam de la Halle and Guillaume de Machaut. It shows how, by blending their craftwith the writing practices of the universities, composers could use refrain "ation to assert their status as authors with a new self-consciousness, and to position works in the vernacular as worthy of study and interpretation. Jennifer Saltzstein is Assistant Professor of Musicology at the University of Oklahoma.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench language. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aMusic. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAuctoritates.  aAuthors.  aLiterature.  aMedieval French Music.  aOld French.  aPoetry.  aScholastic Writing.  aVernacular.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204106140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782041061423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782041061/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles